Vladimir Putin and the Risk of the Third World War
San Francisco — February 24, the Russian invasion of Ukraine marks the beginning of the third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a long meeting on February 4 — the day marking the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two issued a carefully drafted 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and certainly requires detailed negotiations in advance.
I was shocked that Xi seemed to have fully entrusted Putin with the invasion and the war in Ukraine.
He believes that confirming himself as a lifelong ruler of China by the second half of this year is merely a formality, and he is certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream in an unimaginably brutal manner.
A 70-year-old Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it's either now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar who can be blindly followed.
This system is the opposite of a democratic society, and this vision has distorted the emotionally sensitive Russian people's "soul" to an extreme.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I began what I called my political charity work.
Initially, I set up a foundation in my homeland, Hungary, and then actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established a foundation in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I set up a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have been closely following his rise and fully understand his ruthless nature.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but he has seemed to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed notion.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He assumed that the Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but in fact, they are no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Despite the apparent one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out an incredible courageous resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article claiming that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians have been misled by new Nazi agitators.
Since Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not without historical basis.
But in Part 2, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests in 2014.
The 2014 events made him very angry.
But when the Russian army was ordered to attack its Ukrainian brothers, they performed poorly.
The deep-rooted corruption within the Ministry of Defense also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin not only did not blame himself, but seemed to have gone mad.
He has resolved to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seem to have no constraints.
He threw the entire Russian military into battle without regard for all combat rules, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In Mariupol, which is under siege, up to 400,000 people have been without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are delivering defensive weapons to Ukraine while also trying to purchase Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has created a miracle in strengthening European resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has strayed.
On March 8, after China's Foreign Minister Wang Yi firmly stated that the friendship between China and Russia remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
In order to avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to maintain maximum restraint during the war.
It is still uncertain whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
